{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Dynamical Decoupling\n",
    "\n",
    "<p>\n",
    "<font size=4 color=\"#0f62fe\">IBM Quantum Enabling Technologies Team</font>\n",
    "<p>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Information is futile in the Quantum world. Any operation on qubits, as well as qubits just sitting idle, are subject to noise. [Decoherence](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_decoherence) and [Dephasing](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dephasing) effects are driving qubits towards more classical [Mixed states](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_state#Mixed_states). A common technique in Quantum Information Processing in order to prevent these effects is [Dynamical Decoupling](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dynamical_decoupling). We use Dynamical Decoupling in its simplest form, by implementing periodic sequences of gates, which serve to average out unwanted system-enviroment couplings. We focus on decoupling qubits that are idle for some time during a quantum circuit. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<div class=\"alert alert-warning\">\n",
    "Note that the optimal dynamical decoupling strategy depends largely on the involved specific backend and the circuits & algorithms used. The strategies used here should therefore not be seen as 'cooking recipe' but as experimental work which needs to be adapted to the specific situation of your problem and the real hardware you use.\n",
    "</div>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Summary\n",
    "\n",
    "Qiskit offers an in-built [`PadDynamicalDecoupling`](https://qiskit.org/documentation/stubs/qiskit.transpiler.passes.PadDynamicalDecoupling.html) class which allows to fill gaps in quantum circuits with a dynamical decoupling sequence for noise reduction. In order to use it, a pulse schedule needs to be defined by a `PassManager` applied to your circuit. `PadDynamicalDecoupling` scans the circuit for idle periods of time and inserts a sequence of gates in those spots. These gates amount to the identity, so do not change the circuit per se, but have the effect of mitigating decoherence in those idle periods."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Frontmatter\n",
    "\n",
    "Here we load the modules needed for the rest of the notebook, our *.de IBM Quantum account and the real backend we'll use."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from qiskit import *\n",
    "from qiskit.visualization import *\n",
    "\n",
    "#Dynamical Decoupling specific modules\n",
    "from qiskit.circuit.library import XGate\n",
    "from qiskit.transpiler import PassManager, InstructionDurations\n",
    "from qiskit.transpiler.passes import ALAPScheduleAnalysis, PadDynamicalDecoupling\n",
    "from qiskit.quantum_info import hellinger_fidelity\n",
    "\n",
    "#for illustration of backend & qiskit version table\n",
    "import qiskit.tools.jupyter\n",
    "\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "plt.style.use('ibmq-dark')\n",
    "%config InlineBackend.figure_format = 'retina'"
   ]
  },

    "## Example circuit"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let us set up an example circuit that we can try to decouple from noise, in this case a GHZ state as a standard example."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 658.679x325.08 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 6,

      }

    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "circ = QuantumCircuit(4)\n",
    "circ.h(0)\n",
    "circ.cx(0, 1)\n",
    "circ.cx(1, 2)\n",
    "circ.cx(2, 3)\n",
    "circ.measure_all()\n",
    "# \n",
    "durations = InstructionDurations(\n",
    "    [\n",
    "        (\"h\", 0, 50), \n",
    "        (\"cx\", [0, 1], 700), \n",
    "        (\"cx\", [1, 2], 200), \n",
    "        (\"cx\", [2, 3], 300),\n",
    "        (\"measure\", None, 1000),\n",
    "        (\"x\", None, 50)]\n",
    ")\n",
    "circ.draw()"
   ]

    "### Applying Dynamical Decoupling"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {

    "# balanced X-X sequence on all qubits\n",

    "\n",
    "pm = PassManager(\n",
    "    [\n",
    "        ALAPScheduleAnalysis(durations),\n",
    "        PadDynamicalDecoupling(durations, dd_sequence)\n",
    "    ]\n",
    "    )\n",
    "circ_dd = pm.run(circ)\n",
    "circ_dd.draw()"

   "source": [
    "### Varying gate spacing"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "`PadDynamicalDecoupling` allows to vary the time between the dynamical decoupling gates by specifing the parameter `spacing`. One way of doing so was given by Prof. Uhrig of TU Dortmund in his paper [Keeping a Quantum Bit Alive by Optimized π-Pulse Sequences](https://arxiv.org/abs/quant-ph/0609203). We can apply his method in the following way"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1008x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 16,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 279,
       "width": 922
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Uhrig sequence on qubit 0\n",
    "n = 8\n",
    "dd_sequence = [XGate()] * n\n",
    "def uhrig_pulse_location(k):\n",
    "    return np.sin(np.pi * (k + 1) / (2 * n + 2)) ** 2\n",
    "spacing = []\n",
    "for k in range(n):\n",
    "    spacing.append(uhrig_pulse_location(k) - sum(spacing))\n",
    "spacing.append(1 - sum(spacing))\n",
    "\n",
    "pm = PassManager(\n",
    "    [\n",
    "        ALAPScheduleAnalysis(durations),\n",
    "        PadDynamicalDecoupling(durations, dd_sequence, qubits=[0], spacing=spacing),\n",
    "    ]\n",
    ")\n",
    "circ_dd_uhrig = pm.run(circ)\n",
    "timeline_drawer(circ_dd_uhrig)\n",
    "timeline_drawer(circ_dd)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1763.2x325.08 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 17,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 285,
       "width": 1442
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "circ_dd_uhrig_transpiled=transpile(circ_dd_uhrig, backend, scheduling_method=\"alap\",initial_layout=[[23,24,25,22]])\n",
    "circ_dd_uhrig_transpiled.draw(idle_wires=False,fold=-1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 76,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "dd_job_uhrig = backend.run(circ_dd_uhrig_transpiled)"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "We see that Dynamical Decoupling does have effects on the performance of this basic GHZ circuit, however the dynamical decoupling method needs to be carefully chosen."
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Decoupling a mid-circuit measurement"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Measurements take up quite some time in the course of a circuit. Let us see the effects of applying dynamical decoupling during a measurement & reset sequence. This circuit is inspired by the IBM research blog's [introduction](https://www.ibm.com/blogs/research/2021/02/quantum-mid-circuit-measurement/) of mid-circuit measurements."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 628.252x204.68 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 18,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 180,
       "width": 523
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "circ_mid_meas = QuantumCircuit(2,3)\n",
    "circ_mid_meas.h(1)\n",
    "circ_mid_meas.cx(1, 0)\n",
    "circ_mid_meas.h(1)\n",
    "circ_mid_meas.measure(1,2)\n",
    "circ_mid_meas.barrier(0,1)\n",
    "circ_mid_meas.reset(1)\n",
    "circ_mid_meas.cx(0, 1)\n",
    "circ_mid_meas.measure(0,0)\n",
    "circ_mid_meas.measure(1,1)\n",
    "\n",
    "#durations can also be obtained directly from the specific backend\n",
    "durations_backend = InstructionDurations.from_backend(backend)\n",
    "\n",
    "circ_mid_meas.draw()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 30,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {

       " 'granularity': 16,\n",
       " 'min_length': 64,\n",
       " 'pulse_alignment': 1}"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 30,

   ],
   "source": [
    "dd_sequence = [XGate(), XGate()]\n",
    "pm = PassManager([ALAPScheduleAnalysis(durations_backend),\n",
    "                  PadDynamicalDecoupling(durations_backend, dd_sequence,pulse_alignment=backend.configuration().timing_constraints['pulse_alignment'])])\n",
    "circ_dd_midmeas = pm.run(circ_mid_meas_transp)\n",
    "circ_dd_midmeas.draw(idle_wires=False)"

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Application to Bernstein-Vazirani"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The [Bernstein-Vazirani Algorithm](https://qiskit.org/textbook/ch-algorithms/bernstein-vazirani.html) is a modification of the Deutsch-Josza algorithm. It is constructed to learn a string encoded in a function. Its circuits turn out to possess long idle times and have thus [shown to be well-suited](https://gist.github.com/blakejohnson/9d0d7aa8c50350f869ed3eeca185f8f0) for an application of the kind of dynamical decoupling presented. Let us look at this effect in a concise manner. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Setting up the circuit"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 22,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def create_oracle(num_qubits, input_size, secret_int):\n",
    "    # Initialize first n qubits and single ancilla qubit\n",
    "    qc = QuantumCircuit(num_qubits, name=f\"Uf\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    # perform CX for each qubit that matches a bit in secret string\n",
    "    s = ('{0:0' + str(input_size) + 'b}').format(secret_int)\n",
    "    for i_qubit in range(input_size):\n",
    "        if s[input_size - 1 - i_qubit] == '1':\n",
    "            qc.cx(i_qubit, input_size)\n",
    "    return qc\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def bernstein_vazirani(num_qubits, secret_int):\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # size of input is one less than available qubits\n",
    "    input_size = num_qubits - 1\n",
    "\n",
    "    # setup circuit\n",
    "    qc = QuantumCircuit(num_qubits, input_size, name=\"main\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    # put ancilla in |1> state\n",
    "    qc.x(input_size)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # start with Hadamard on all qubits, including ancilla\n",
    "    for i_qubit in range(num_qubits):\n",
    "         qc.h(i_qubit)\n",
    "\n",
    "    qc.barrier()\n",
    "\n",
    "    # generate Uf oracle\n",
    "    Uf = create_oracle(num_qubits, input_size, secret_int)\n",
    "    qc.append(Uf, range(num_qubits))\n",
    "\n",
    "    qc.barrier()\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Hadamard again on all non-ancilla qubits,\n",
    "    for i_qubit in range(input_size):\n",
    "         qc.h(i_qubit)\n",
    "\n",
    "    qc.barrier()\n",
    "\n",
    "    # measure all data qubits\n",
    "    for i in range(input_size):\n",
    "        qc.measure(i, i)\n",
    "\n",
    "    return qc"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 23,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 748.797x385.28 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 23,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 326,
       "width": 620
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "bv_circuit_test = bernstein_vazirani(5, int('1101', 2))\n",
    "bv_circuit_test.draw('mpl')"
   ]
  },

   "metadata": {},

    "Can't we do better than this? \n",
    "\n",
    "### Apply Dynamical Decoupling"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 26,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "durations_backend = InstructionDurations.from_backend(backend)\n",
    "dd_sequence = [XGate(), XGate()]\n",
    "pm = PassManager([ALAPScheduleAnalysis(durations_backend),\n",
    "                  PadDynamicalDecoupling(durations_backend, dd_sequence,pulse_alignment=backend.configuration().timing_constraints['pulse_alignment'])])\n",
    "\n",
    "# transpile and view the resulting schedule\n",
    "circ_dd_bv = pm.run(bv_transpiled)\n",
    "#timeline_drawer(circ_dd_bv)"
   ]
  },
  {
